1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. c3 Nf6 5. d4 exd4 6. cxd4 Bb4+ 7. Nc3 $6 {A
well-known Gambit, which is quite popular among amateurs, but objectively
dubious. I have only one recommendation for Black players - to study this line!
} Nxe4 8. O-O ({Not dangerous for Black is} 8. d5 {in view of} Nxc3 9. bxc3
Bxc3+ 10. Bd2 Bxd2+ 11. Qxd2 Ne7 {and White has hardly enough for being two
pawns down, for example} 12. O-O d6 13. Rfe1 O-O 14. Rac1 Bd7 15. Bd3 h6 $17 {
0-1 (18) Galera,T (2050)-Ralls,R (2145) IECG email 2003}) 8... Bxc3 ({It's
well-know that Black shouldn't play} 8... Nxc3 9. bxc3 Bxc3 $2 (9... d5 $1 {
still a good line for Black.}) 10. Ba3 $1 $40 {with a dangerous initiative for
White.}) 9. d5 ({Black's task is easier after} 9. bxc3 d5 $1 10. Bd3 O-O 11.
Qc2 Re8 12. Re1 Bf5 13. Rb1 b6 $1 {and White has no sufficient compensation
for being pawn down. This has been played eight times.}) 9... Bf6 (9... Ne5 {
is another good line for Black.}) 10. Re1 {This is the main continuation. In
the future, White will be trying to create some pressure along the e-file.} ({
Clearly worse is} 10. dxc6 bxc6 11. Re1 d5 12. Bd3 O-O $17) 10... Ne7 11. Rxe4
d6 12. Bg5 {By far White's first choice in this position. White is trying not
only to eliminate the defender of the e7-knight but also to activate his own
knight.} ({It's important to mention that the super-aggressive} 12. g4 {
doesn't yield White an initiative. For example, after} h6 13. h4 c6 14. g5 hxg5
15. hxg5 Be5 $1 16. Nxe5 dxe5 17. Bf4 cxd5 18. Bb5+ Bd7 19. Bxd7+ Qxd7 20. Rxe5
O-O $17 {Black is much better Rubio Doblas,R (2141)-Brandhorst,W (2477) ICCF
email 2007}) 12... Bxg5 13. Nxg5 h6 {The most simple, while} (13... O-O 14.
Nxh7 $1 {leads to some wild complications.}) 14. Qe2 {The positional play
doesn't work anymore for White} (14. Qh5 O-O 15. Rae1 Nf5 16. Nf3 g6 17. Qh3 h5
18. Bd3 Qf6 $17 {and White has no compensation whatsoever Schiffers,S (2103)
-Fedorchuk,S (2657) Maastricht 2015}) 14... hxg5 15. Re1 Be6 $1 {Another
important  and very precise move that we must know. After closing the e-file,
Black has no problems at all.} 16. dxe6 f6 {It might look scary at first
glance, especially with White's powerful pawn on e6. However it transpires
that Black is clearly better due to a clear plan of queenside castle , where
Black king would be safe and his material advantage should tell.} 17. Re3 {
This is considered to be White's best try. However, it's hardly dangerous and
Black can maintain much better game with accurate defense.} c6 $1 18. Rh3 {
This is the point. After exchanging the h8-rook, the white queen will be
trying to invade Black's camp. Nevertheless, Black has enough resources to
prevent the opponent from executing this idea.} Rxh3 19. gxh3 g6 $1 {After
this precise move, Black has no any problems. Now the king is heading for the
g7-square.} 20. b4 Kf8 21. h4 gxh4 22. Qg4 Kg7 $17 {Black has gained a clear
edge on has won convincingly.} 23. Qxh4 d5 24. Bd3 Qd6 25. f4 Qxb4 26. Qg3 Rh8
27. Rb1 Qd4+ 28. Kh1 b6 29. Rg1 Rh6 30. Re1 c5 31. Re2 Qa1+ 32. Kg2 Qd1 33. f5
Rh5 34. h4 Rxh4 35. Qxh4 Qxd3 36. Qg4 c4 37. Qf3 Qd1 38. Kf2 Qd4+ 39. Kg2 g5
40. Qh5 Qd3 41. Qf7+ Kh6 42. Qxf6+ Kh5 43. Qe5 Nxf5 44. e7 Nh4+ 45. Kf2 Qf3+
46. Ke1 Qh1+ 47. Kd2 Nf3+ 48. Kc2 Nxe5 49. e8=Q+ Ng6 50. Qf7 Kh6 51. Re6 Qg2+
52. Kc3 Qg3+ 53. Kb4 Qd3 54. Qf8+ Kh5 55. Qf7 Qb1+ 56. Ka3 Qd3+ 57. Kb4 c3 58.
Qh7+ Kg4 59. Qxg6 Qc4+ 60. Ka3 c2 61. Re1 Qc3+ 0-1

