1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. c3 Nf6 5. d4 {From a historical perspective,
this is one of the oldest continuations in the position. White is trying to
occupy the centre as soon as possible. The modern practice, however, managed
to prove that Black has enough resources to challenge White's central strategy.
} exd4 6. cxd4 Bb4+ {Without this check, Black's position would be simply bad.
The reader probably knows that when playing a rook down (a1-rook), old masters
like Greco started their games with a pawn on a3! The reason was obvious - in
this position, the move 6...Bb4 wouldn't be possible.} 7. Bd2 Bxd2+ 8. Nbxd2 d5
$1 {An important move, which allows Black to have a comfortable game,
otheriwse Black would be in trouble. Now, we are going to enter an IQP
position.} 9. exd5 Nxd5 10. Qb3 {White tries to put some pressure on d5,
before Black completes the development. We know that in positions with an
isolated queen's pawn, the control over the d5-square is of a crucial
importance.} ({Another direction is} 10. O-O O-O 11. Rc1 {This move is
directed against the line 11...Nb6 12.Bb3 Nxd4 which could be now answered by
13.Nxd4 Qxd4 14.Rxc7.} ({White main alternative here is} 11. Re1 Nb6 12. Bb3
Bg4 {This leads to more complex game to compare with} (12... Nxd4 13. Nxd4 Qxd4
14. Qc2 {here White compensation is enough to maintain balance} c6 15. Ne4 Bf5
16. Qc5 $1 Qxc5 17. Nxc5 $44 {1/2-1/2 (22) Khorunzhy,M (2221)-Petukhov,V (2232)
ICCF email 2012[%csl Gb7][%cal Ge1e7]}) 13. h3 Bh5 14. g4 Bg6 15. Rc1 Qd6 16.
Ne4 Bxe4 17. Rxe4 Rad8 {with double-edged play Andrade,J-Delgado,L (1896) ICCF
email 2010}) 11... Nb6 12. Bb3 a5 $1 {This is a thematic idea for the
variation. Black intends to gain space on the queenside by means of a7-a5-a4
advance. Later on, he could even consider activating his queen's rook by
playing Ra5.} 13. Nc4 ({In case of} 13. a4 {White is weakening the important
b4-square. Here I like the following game[%csl Gb4]} Bg4 14. h3 Bh5 15. Rc5 Bg6
16. Qc1 {Aitbayev,A (2420)-Jumabayev,R (2561) Astana 2014  Here Black missed
an elegant solution} Nb4 17. Ne5 (17. Rxc7 {is too risky in view of} Nd3 18.
Qc3 Nf4 $1 {with double threat 19...Ne2 and 19...Nbd5[%cal Gf4e2,Gb6d5]} 19.
Qc5 Nxa4 {and Black is clearly better.[%cal Gf4e6]}) 17... c6 {and Black has
very comfortable game.}) 13... Nxc4 14. Bxc4 Bg4 $1 {Black easily obtained a
comfortable game in recent game} 15. d5 Ne5 16. Be2 Bxf3 17. Bxf3 Qd6 {0-1 (54)
Harikrishna,P (2753)-Tomashevsky,E (2728) Huaian 2016}) 10... Nce7 {Maybe a
bit passive move, but Black is trying to complicate matters.} ({His problem is
that after} 10... Na5 11. Qa4+ Nc6 12. Qb3 ({After} 12. O-O O-O {It's probably
White's worst version of isolated pawn in this line due to the misplaced
position of his queen} 13. Qc2 Nb6 14. Qc3 Nxc4 15. Nxc4 Ne7 $15 {Black is
already better Khorunzhy,M (2331)-Szabo,V (2386) LSS email 2010}) 12... Na5 {
we have a draw by repetition.}) 11. O-O O-O 12. Rfe1 c6 {Many games have been
played in this position, but the following line looks as a critical one} 13.
Ne4 Qb6 ({Deserves attention} 13... Nb6 14. Bd3 Ned5 {a good example here} 15.
Nc5 Rb8 16. Rac1 Nf4 17. Bb1 {this happened in  Van den Doel,E (2599)-Sokolov,
I (2690) Leeuwarden 2004 and now Black should have played} Bg4 $1 18. Ne5 Qg5
$132 {with interesting play.}) 14. Qa3 {Here my choice would be} a5 $5 15. Nc5
Qc7 (15... Qb4 $1 {looks more convincing} 16. Qd3 Bf5 17. Qe2 Rad8 $11 {with
easy equality.}) 16. Rac1 b6 $6 {Better would have been} (16... Bf5 17. Qb3 b6
18. Ne4 Rac8 $11) 17. Ne4 Bb7 18. Ne5 Rad8 19. Qg3 (19. Nc3 $36) 19... Qc8 20.
h3 Nf5 21. Qg4 Nxd4 22. Qxc8 Bxc8 23. Nxc6 Nxc6 24. Bxd5 Rxd5 25. Rxc6 Re5 26.
Re3 Bb7 27. Rxb6 Bxe4 28. f3 f5 29. fxe4 fxe4 30. b4 axb4 31. Rxb4 Rfe8 32. Kf2
Kf7 33. a4 Kf6 34. Ra3 h5 35. a5 Rf5+ 36. Ke2 e3 37. Rxe3 Rxe3+ 38. Kxe3 Rxa5
1/2-1/2

