1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. c3 Nf6 5. d4 exd4 6. e5 {Important direction
in this line and I can easily call it the pet line of Baadur Jobava.} d5 $1 {
A very thematic counter-strike in 1. e4 e5 side-lines.} 7. Bb5 {Definitely the
main move here.} (7. Be2 {This modest looking move is designed to discourage
Black from playing ...Bg4 in the future. As the reader is going to see later,
the pin along the a5-d1 diagonal could be very annoying.} d3 $5 {Very concrete
approach which helps Black to avoid the main theoretical line. If White
doesn't play energetically, the e5-pawn will be weak.} ({Black most poular
response here is} 7... Ne4 8. cxd4 Bb6 ({Baadur Jobava won a sensational game
after} 8... Bb4+ 9. Bd2 Nxd2 10. Nbxd2 O-O 11. O-O f6 12. Rc1 Kh8 13. Nb3 Bg4
14. a3 Be7 15. Re1 $14 {1-0 (28) Jobava,B (2702)-Karjakin,S (2786) Loo 2013})
9. Nc3 O-O 10. O-O Be6 11. Be3 f6 12. exf6 Qxf6 {with complex game  Habu,Y 
(2398)-Georgiev,K (2627) Zuerich 2015}) 8. exf6 {White's only chance to fight
for an advantage, since after both} (8. Qxd3 Ng4 {and[%csl Ge5,Gf2]}) (8. Bxd3
Ng4 {Black is clearly better.[%csl Ge5,Gf2]}) 8... dxe2 9. Qxe2+ Kf8 10. Be3 {
Another try for White} (10. b4 Bd6 11. b5 Na5 12. Bg5 Qe8 13. Qxe8+ Kxe8 14.
fxg7 Rg8 15. Bf6 Be7 16. Bxe7 Kxe7 17. Nbd2 a6 18. a4 {as occurred in Jobava,B
(2717)-Timman,J (2601) Hoogeveen 2014 Black should have played} Kf6 $1 $146 19.
O-O Kxg7 20. Rfe1 axb5 21. axb5 Bd7 $11 {with balanced position.}) 10... Bxe3
11. fxg7+ Kxg7 12. fxe3 ({Obviously} 12. Qxe3 $4 {would run into} Re8 {[%csl
Ge1,Ge3]}) 12... Re8 13. O-O Qe7 14. Re1 Bf5 15. Nbd2 {In this position draw
was agreed, however I like Black's chances after 15...Bg6 1/2-1/2 (15)
Nisipeanu,L (2654)-Ragger,M (2688) Helsingor 2015 CBM 167 Extra [Avrukh,B]})
7... Ne4 8. cxd4 Bb6 9. h3 $5 {This is White's latest word in this variation.
From a logical point of view, it is easy to understand this move - White
spends a tempo on preventing Black from playing 9...Bg4. Black has to play
extremely energetically in order not to find himself in a passive position.} ({
The main move has been always considered to be} 9. Nc3 {after} O-O 10. Be3 {
Black has the strong} Bg4 {We have reached on of the critical position of the
entire variation. White has a space advantage but Black has enough resources
to challenge White's centre. Besides the pressure against the central d4-pawn,
Black could eliminate White's spatial advantage by means of f7-f6. In this way,
his rook comes into play and the pressure along the f-file might become
serious.} 11. h3 {Other moves here:} ({Hardly a good idea for White is} 11.
Bxc6 bxc6 {especially taking into account that} 12. Qa4 $6 {is convincingly
refuted by means of[%csl Gc6]} f6 $1 13. Qxc6 Nxc3 14. bxc3 Bxf3 15. gxf3 fxe5
16. dxe5 Bxe3 17. fxe3 Rxf3 18. Ke2 Rf8 {and White should fight hard in order
to survive  Vohl,G (2446)-Sychov,A (2200) ICCF email 2010[%csl Ge2]}) ({Quite
a reasonable option is} 11. Qc2 {White not only attacks the e4-knight but at
the same time is ready to answer moves like f7-f6 and f7-f5 by means of Nxd5.
Black played very impressive in the following game} Bf5 12. Qb3 Na5 $1 {Very
strong} 13. Qa4 ({Black's central pawn is untouchable in view of} 13. Qxd5 $2
Qe7 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Ga8d8]} 14. e6 (14. Nxe4 {loses to} Be6 $1 {[%csl Gd5]}
15. Nf6+ gxf6 16. Qe4 Qb4+ $1 {[%csl Gb5]}) 14... fxe6 15. Qe5 Rad8 $17 {and
White's queen is still in danger.}) 13... c6 14. Be2 Nxc3 15. bxc3 Bc7 {[%cal
Gb7b5]} 16. Bg5 Qd7 17. O-O h6 18. Bh4 b5 19. Qd1 Nc4 {and Black had nothing
to worry about Bachmann,A (2609)-Swiercz,D (2665) Moscow 2016}) 11... Bh5 12.
O-O {White has also tried} (12. Qc2 {here we have a Top level game} Bg6 13. Qb3
Ne7 14. Nh4 c5 $1 15. Nxg6 hxg6 16. dxc5 Nxc5 17. Bxc5 Bxc5 18. O-O Bd4 $11 {
and Black equalized in  Ivanchuk,V (2731)-Kramnik,V (2793) Antalya 2013}) {It
looks like Black can force draw by means of} 12... Nxd4 $5 (12... f6 {leads to
more complicated game.}) 13. Bxd4 Bxf3 14. gxf3 Qg5+ 15. Kh1 Qf5 16. Nxd5 Qxh3+
17. Kg1 Ng3 18. fxg3 Qxg3+ 19. Kh1 Qh3+ {1/2-1/2 (21) Canizares Cuadra,P (2300)
-Sanchez Rodenas,A (2336) ICCF email 2013}) 9... O-O 10. O-O f6 $1 {Definitely
the most principled line. Black is always happy to trade White's central pawn.}
11. Bxc6 {White wants to release the pressure against his central pawns.} ({
Another option is} 11. Nc3 fxe5 12. Bxc6 bxc6 13. Nxe4 (13. Nxe5 $2 {just bad
in view of} Nxf2 $1 14. Rxf2 Rxf2 15. Kxf2 Qh4+ 16. Kf1 Ba6+ 17. Ne2 Bxd4 $19 {
with winning attack Maly,M (1398)-Slivova,V (1753) Havirov 2008}) 13... dxe4
14. Nxe5 Ba6 15. Qb3+ Qd5 16. Rd1 Be2 17. Rd2 Qxb3 18. axb3 Bb5 $11 {1/2-1/2 
(50) Feltan,M (2081)-Lacrosse,M (2198) Rijeka 2010}) 11... bxc6 12. Be3 fxe5 (
12... f5 $5 {might be interesting alternative for Black.}) 13. Nxe5 Ba6 14. Re1
Ba5 {This leads to forced draw, while I am not sure Black has sufficient
compensation after} (14... Qh4 {Kiroski,T (2362)-Georgiev,V (2586) Struga 2010}
15. Nf3 $1 $146 Rxf3 (15... Qf6 16. Nc3 $14) 16. Qxf3 Rf8 17. Qg4 Qf6 18. Nc3
Nxf2 19. Qg3) 15. Nxc6 Qh4 $3 {Very-well calculated sacrifice} 16. Nxa5 (16.
Re2 Bxe2 17. Qxe2 Bb6 {only can be better for Black.}) 16... Rxf2 17. Nc3 Rxg2+
$1 18. Kxg2 Qg3+ 19. Kh1 Qxh3+ 20. Kg1 Qg3+ 21. Kh1 Qh3+ 22. Kg1 Qg3+ 23. Kh1
Qh3+ 1/2-1/2

