1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. O-O Nf6 5. d4 {A very old Gambit, which has
been employed for the first time in 1853! White sacrifices a pawn in order to
exploit his better development.} Bxd4 $1 {In my opinion the most principled
response to White's aggressive approach.} (5... exd4 6. e5 d5 {leads to Max
Lange Attack , which is more complicated choice to compare with 5...Bxd4}) 6.
Nxd4 Nxd4 7. f4 {White plays very energetically - he tries to open new files
and diagonals.} ({The most popular alternative is} 7. Bg5 {but you can hardly
see this move in the games of strong players. Black's best reaction is} h6 8.
Bh4 Qe7 ({The natural} 8... g5 $6 {runs into the unexpected} 9. f4 $1 {with
dangerous initiative.}) 9. Nc3 (9. f4 {is easily refuted by means of} Qc5 $1 {
[%csl Gc4,Gg1]} 10. fxe5 Nf3+ 11. Kh1 Nxh4 12. exf6 Qxc4 13. Na3 Qc5 14. Qe1 g5
$19 {with winning advantage Bergez,L (2344)-Taylor,W (1993) Castell de Sant
Ferran 2016}) 9... g5 10. Bg3 d6 11. f4 {Thematic tactical idea} c6 (11... gxf4
12. Bh4 {looks a bit annoying.[%cal Gh4e7]}) 12. fxe5 dxe5 {and it seems Black
has solid pawn up  Noble,R-Graham,S (2243) ICCF email 2010}) 7... d6 8. fxe5 ({
I would to mention also} 8. c3 Nc6 9. f5 {that has been played quite a lot.}
Ne7 $1 {The right plan. Black should prepare the d6-d5 break in the center.}
10. Qf3 d5 $5 ({There is nothing wrong with} 10... c6 {[%cal Gd6d5]}) 11. exd5
Qd6 (11... Bxf5 12. Bg5 {gives White some play.}) 12. Bb5+ c6 13. Ba4 (13. dxc6
$2 Qc5+ {loses piece.[%csl Gb5,Gg1]}) 13... Qxd5 14. Qxd5 Nfxd5 {and Black was
just a healthy pawn up in  Stephan,C-Stanulis,J (2382) ICCF email 2002}) 8...
dxe5 9. Bg5 {White's main idea in this line. The pin along h4-d8 diagonal
looks very annoying. However Black can easily handle this situation and
prepare castle queenside.} Qe7 $1 {I would suugest not to rush with 9...Be6 as
in many cases we can play Bd7.} 10. Na3 {The most challenging move, the rest
is too easy for Black} (10. c3 Ne6 11. Bxf6 gxf6 {Black can even simplify by
means of} (11... Qc5+ 12. Kh1 Qxc4 13. Bxe5 Qxe4 14. Bxc7 {White is able to
regain the pawn, but Black achieves a very comfortable position with slight
pull} ({Another pawn is untouchable} 14. Bxg7 $2 Rg8 $40 {[%csl Gg2]}) 14...
O-O 15. Bg3 b6 {[%cal Gc8b7]} 16. Nd2 Qc6 17. Qf3 Bb7 18. Qxc6 Bxc6 {and
despite the serious simplifications and diiferent colour bishops Black has a
slight edge, thanks to more active bishop Bakalchuk,J (2272)-Hracek,Z (2631)
Jerusalem 2015}) 12. Na3 Nf4 {Black has a great game as in the following
example} 13. Kh1 h5 14. Qf3 Bg4 15. Qf2 h4 {and Black was just better in
Lipecki,A-Gabris,V (2343) ICCF email 2010}) 10... Bd7 {Black naturally
prepares the queenside caslte.[%cal Ge8c8]} ({Surprisingly,} 10... Rg8 {has
been fashionable recently, where Black anticipates capture on f6 and prepares
to fight for the open g-file. However, I would prefer the more natural
approach with 10...Bd7}) 11. Qe1 {Probably White's best continuation here.} ({
White's main alternative} 11. c3 {leads to a fantastic game for Black.} Ne6 12.
Bxf6 gxf6 13. Qf3 Nf4 $1 {Now} 14. g3 Nh3+ 15. Kh1 {has been played twice, but
I found a very powerful novelty} h5 $1 $146 {It transpires that not only White
can attack in this variation. The approximate line here would be[%csl Gh1]
[%cal Gh5h4]} 16. Qxf6 Qxf6 17. Rxf6 h4 $1 {and Black's initiative on the
kingside looks very powerful.[%csl Gh1]}) 11... Ne6 12. Bxf6 ({Most probably} 
12. Bh4 {which occurred only once in  Nogal,J (2315)-Bucsa,I (2085) ICCF email
2010 can be an improvement for White.} {Here I would recommend the following
idea} h6 $5 $146 {with idea to get rid of annoying pin by means of 13...Ng5
[%cal Ge6g5]}) 12... gxf6 13. Qe3 ({Worse is} 13. Qf2 Nf4 14. Kh1 f5 $5 (14...
h5 {also looks strong with the following idea:} 15. g3 Nh3 16. Qxf6 Qxf6 17.
Rxf6 h4 $40 {and Black has nice initiative on the kingside.}) 15. exf5 {Li,R 
(2446)-Banawa,J (2359) Saint Louis 2015} {Now surprising} a6 $1 {covering
b5-square and preparing Bc6 at the same time would have been extremely strong.
It's hard to imagine what White can do to prevent Black's initiative.[%cal
Gd7c6]}) 13... Rg8 14. Rf2 Rg6 15. Raf1 Nf4 (15... b6 $1 $17 {with idea of
queenside castle would have secured Black's advantage.[%csl Ga7][%cal Ge3b6]})
16. Kh1 a6 17. g3 Nh3 18. Rd2 Bg4 19. Be2 Bxe2 1/2-1/2

