1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. O-O Nf6 5. d3 O-O $5 {Purposely delaying
d7-d6- move in order to have possibility to play d7-d5 at once.} 6. c3 {This
is the move Black was waiting for. Due to the vulnerability of the d3-pawn,
Black can carry out the thematic} d5 $5 {The reader should remmember that we
play this move only when White had played c2-c3. In the arising positions,
White's pressure against the central e5-pawn will be compensated by the
weakness on d3. The play becomes extremely dynamic and a lot of precision is
required.} 7. exd5 Nxd5 {This position has been very fashionable lately .
White has a variety of decent moves.  Let's look at them separately.} 8. a4 {
This is White's latest attempt to fight for opening advantage. Of course, the
idea to gain space on the queenside is quite typical for the Italian game.
White has been also trying other moves and they have a lot!} (8. Nbd2 {The
idea of this move is to bring the knight into the centre by playing Ne4. The
main drawback is that after} Nb6 {Black could make use of the vulnerability of
the d3-pawn. White's bishop couldn't remain on the a2-g8 - diagonal.[%csl Rd3]}
9. Bb5 Bd6 {By protecting the e5-pawn, Black prepares the typical Ne7-g6
followed by a7-a6 when White must part with his b5-bishop. That is why White
should put additional pressure on e5 by means of[%csl Ge5][%cal Gc6e7,Ga7a6,
Gd6e5]} 10. Re1 Bg4 {This pin is a typical way to protect the e5-pawn in this
variation.} 11. h3 Bh5 12. Ne4 ({Another good example is} 12. a4 {As in the
main line, White's idea is to bother the b6-knight by means of a4-a5. We
should prevent it by playing} a5 13. Ne4 Na7 {It becomes clear that White's
annoying bishop will be eliminated.} 14. d4 Nxb5 15. axb5 Bxf3 16. Qxf3 exd4
17. cxd4 Bb4 $1 {Black was perfectly fine in Shankland,S (2661)-Sevian,S (2531)
Saint Louis 2015}) 12... Re8 ({It seems like Black is doing fine also after} 
12... f5 13. Ng3 Bxf3 14. Qxf3 Qd7 $1 {One of the high-level games here went}
15. a4 a6 16. Bxc6 bxc6 17. c4 $6 Rab8 {and Black was already better in Wei,Y 
(2714)-Vidit,S (2648) Abu Dhabi 2016}) 13. Bg5 f6 14. Be3 a6 15. Bxc6 bxc6 16.
Ng3 Bf7 {Black reached a comfortable equality in Carlsen,M (2855)-Aronian,L 
(2792) Leuven 2016. His pair of bishops and space advantage in the centre
compensate the doubled pawns on the c-file.}) ({Another well known idea is} 8.
Re1 {With starts attacking the e5-pawn without wasting time.} Bg4 {Again, this
pin is the best way to defend the pawn. Note that the move 8...Re8 would be a
typical mistake in view of 9.d3-d4 where Black loses at least a pawn.} 9. h3
Bh5 10. Nbd2 Nb6 {We are already familiar with this idea. The move ...Nb6 is
always a decent reaction when the d3-pawn is not protected.} 11. b4 (11. Bb5 {
transposes to 8. Nbd2}) 11... Be7 {Now the critical game seems to me} 12. Qe2 {
White can win the central pawn by means of} (12. b5 Na5 13. g4 Bg6 14. Nxe5 {
but Black retains a nice compensation after} Bf6 $1 {for example} 15. Nxg6 hxg6
16. Ne4 Naxc4 17. dxc4 Nxc4 $11 {1/2-1/2 (33) Jovanovic,Z (2550)-Bosiocic,M 
(2555) Austria 2014}) 12... Nxc4 13. Nxc4 f6 14. b5 {White has to play
energetic in order not to get worse positionally} Nb8 15. d4 a6 $1 {A great
way to generate a counterplay. Blac k opens up the position and brings his
a8-rook into play.} 16. bxa6 Rxa6 17. dxe5 {all this happened in Vocaturo,D 
(2574)-Hammer,J (2689) Gjakova 2016 , now Black should have continued} Nd7 $1
$146 18. g4 Bf7 {Black's active pieces and the pair of bishop compensate the
missing pawn. Furthermore, White has a weakened king and a damaged pawn
structure.}) ({Sometimes, before attacking the e5-pawn, White prevents the
move ...Bg4 by means of} 8. h3 {In this way, however, he loses a valuable time
which gives Black the opportunity to create pressure against the d3-pawn.} Nb6
9. Bb5 ({In my opinion too passive} 9. Bb3 Bf5 {[%csl Gd3]} 10. Bc2 Qd7 {Black
has comfortable game as in the following game} 11. Nh4 Be6 12. Nd2 f5 13. Qh5
$6 Rae8 14. Nb3 Bd6 $15 {Ardelean,R (1702)-Sohier,J (2240) Arad 2016}) {Now I
like} 9... f6 $1 {despite 9...Bd6 being more popular. Generally, when it is
possible, the bishop should stay on the a7-g1 diagonal.} 10. Nbd2 Qd5 $1 {
threatening 11...Bxf2 followed up by 12...Qxb5[%csl Gb5][%cal Gc5f2]} 11. d4
exd4 12. Nb3 Bd6 13. Nbxd4 Nxd4 14. Nxd4 Be5 $11 {Black equalised comfortably
in Nemeth,M (2492)-Erdos,V (2651) Zalakaros 2014}) ({It is interesting to
mention that in response to} 8. b4 {Black's best is} Be7 {In this particular
position, the b6-square is not very suitable for the bishop, since the advance
of White's queenside pawns could be annoying.} 9. Re1 ({It's already
well-known that} 9. b5 Na5 10. Bxd5 Qxd5 11. c4 Qd7 $1 {is good for Black. One
of the model games here continued} 12. Bd2 e4 $1 {[%csl Gc4,Gd3]} 13. Bxa5 exf3
14. Qxf3 a6 $1 {The first step towards activating our light-squared bishop.
[%csl Gc8]} 15. bxa6 Rxa6 16. Bc3 b5 17. Nd2 $6 (17. cxb5 {was better,
although after} Rb6 $1 {Black has a nice compensation.[%cal Gc8b7,Gb6g6]})
17... b4 18. Bb2 c5 $40 {Black was already better in Yudin,S (2546)-Vallejo
Pons,F (2698) Dubai 2014[%csl Gd3][%cal Gc8b7,Ga6g6]}) 9... Bf6 {This is one
of the ideas behind the move 8...Be7. By tranferring his bishop to f6, Black
wants to make use of the weakened long diagonal. One of the recent games
continued} 10. Bg5 Bxg5 11. Nxg5 Nf4 $1 12. Nf3 Bg4 $15 {When Black is better
due to his more active pieces and lead in development.  Savchenko,B (2602)
-Adhiban,B (2671) Abu Dhabi 2016}) 8... Nb6 9. Bb5 Ne7 $1 {Again, Black is
going for this thematic knight retreat. The idea is clear - Black wants to
challenge White's misplaced b5-bishop.} ({Worse is} 9... Bd6 {as it allows} 10.
a5 Nd5 11. a6 $1 {and White is definitely better Demchenko,A (2596)-Jakovenko,
D (2745) Khanty-Mansiysk 2014}) 10. a5 ({A very important alternative is} 10.
Nxe5 c6 11. Bc4 Bd6 $1 {A very concrete play} 12. Nf3 (12. Nxf7 Rxf7 13. Bxf7+
Kxf7 {looks good for Black.}) 12... Nxc4 13. dxc4 Qc7 14. Re1 {This position
was reached in the game Sedina,E (2275)-Loiacono,A (2085) Trieste. I think
that after the precise} Bf5 $146 {Black could claim a nice compensation thanks
to his powerful bishop's pair.}) 10... c6 {Now we have a pretty forced
sequence of moves} 11. axb6 cxb5 12. Rxa7 Rxa7 13. bxa7 Bxa7 14. Nxe5 Bf5 $1
$44 {It transpires that Black has a very interesting play for the pawn mainly
due to his active bishop's pair.} 15. Re1 {Other examples here:} (15. Na3 Bb8
16. d4 {Mamedov,R (2666)-Balogh,C (2614) Baku 2016  The surprising} b4 $1 $146
17. cxb4 Be6 $44 {would give Black nice compensation.}) (15. Be3 Bb8 16. d4 {
this occured in  Milliet,S (2346)-Hammer,J (2689) Drancy 2016   A very natural}
f6 $146 17. Nf3 Nd5 $44 {should have been played. The activity of Black's
pieces and the pair of bishops compensate the missing pawn.}) 15... Bb8 16. Na3
b4 $1 {Wesley has done a great opening work in this line. Black is able to
hold without too much difficulties} 17. cxb4 Qd5 18. Nec4 Bxd3 19. Rxe7 Bxc4
20. Qxd5 Bxd5 $11 21. Rd7 Bc6 22. Rd1 Ba4 23. Rd3 Bc7 24. b3 Bc6 25. f3 Rd8 26.
Rxd8+ Bxd8 27. b5 Bd7 28. Kf2 Be7 29. Ke2 Bxa3 30. Bxa3 Bxb5+ 1/2-1/2

