1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. c3 Nf6 5. d3 a6 6. Bb3 {The old-fashioned
variation, which leads to very positional play.} d6 {There is almost no
difference if Black would play first 5...d6 and then 6...a6} 7. O-O O-O 8. h3 {
White takes control over g4-square in order to avoid Black's knight jump. We
have reached the main position of the so-called classical Giuoco Piano. White
has two possibile plans in this position:  1) prepare the d3-d4 advance by
playing Re1, Nbd2-f1-g3  2) develop a kingside attack by playing Re1,
Nbd2-f1-g3 followed by Nh2 and Qf3.   On the other hand, Black should try to
challenge the strong b3-bishop and execture the d6-d5 break in the most
suitable moment.} h6 {This is prophylaxis against a possible Bg5.} 9. Re1 Re8 {
This move helps to preapare Be6 and in general determines Black's strategy to
keep dark-squared bishop as much as possible on c5 ( not playing Ba7), trying
to get it to f8 after the thematic advance in the center d6-d5.} 10. Nbd2 Be6
$1 {Getting rid of White's pressure along a2-g8 diagonal is one of Black
essential ideas in this variation.} 11. Nf1 ({An obvious alternative here
would be} 11. Bc2 {when Black is ready to carry out} d5 12. exd5 ({Another
popular direction here is} 12. Qe2 Bf8 $1 {the best square for Black
dark-squared bishop. Now, a possible knight-transfer to f5 is not an issue
anymore.} 13. exd5 Qxd5 14. Ne4 Nxe4 15. dxe4 Qb5 $1 16. Bd3 Qa4 {Black queen
is quite annoying and White decided to force draw by repeation.} 17. Bc2 Qb5
18. Bd3 Qa4 19. Bc2 Qb5 {1/2-1/2 (19) Gelfand,B (2758)-Aronian,L (2786) Moscow
2009}) 12... Bxd5 13. b4 {This line has been quite fashionable recently.} Ba7 {
This is one of the rare cases where I prefer to put the bishop on a7. This
could be explained by the fact that Black has a clear plan to put pressure
against the f2-pawn.} 14. a4 b5 $1 {Sooner or later Black has to stop b4-b5
idea.} 15. Bb2 Qb8 $5 {Trying to activate the queen via b6-square.} ({Very
reasonable for Black looks} 15... Bb6 16. Rc1 Rb8 {with normal game for Black
Kadric,D (2546)-Sevian,S (2580) Dallas 2016}) 16. Nf1 Qb6 17. Ne3 Rad8 18. a5
Qb7 19. Nxd5 Nxd5 $13 {with very unclear play Hou,Y (2673)-Eljanov,P (2760)
Wijk aan Zee 2016}) 11... Bxb3 ({There is nothing wrong with immediate} 11...
d5 {here is one illustrative line} 12. exd5 Bxd5 13. Be3 Bf8 14. Ng3 Bxb3 $1 {
This looks like the most simple solution.} (14... Na5 15. Bc2 c5 16. a3 Nc6 17.
Nd2 b5 18. a4 Qc7 $11 {not bad either as in  Adhiban,B (2671)-Ponomariov,R 
(2709) Baku 2016}) 15. axb3 a5 {Very ambitious move. Black believes White
b3-pawn might be weak in long-term[%csl Gb3]} 16. Qc2 {too passive. Better
would have been} (16. d4 exd4 17. Nxd4 {with equality.}) 16... Qd7 17. Rad1
Rad8 $15 {and Black was slightly better thanks to his space advantage in Vovk,
A (2599)-Durarbayli,V (2559) Al Ain 2013}) 12. axb3 ({In case of} 12. Qxb3 {
Black shouldn't waste time for defending the b7-pawn, since it's not really
hanging!} d5 {b7-pawn is untouchable} 13. Ng3 (13. Qxb7 $4 Na5 {White queen is
trapped.[%csl Gb7]}) 13... Qd7 14. Bd2 Bb6 15. Rad1 Rad8 16. Bc1 Qe6 $11 {
Black has equalized comfortably in Paehtz,E (2472)-Mkrtchian,L (2434) Huaian
2016}) 12... d5 13. Qe2 Bf8 $1 {My favourite square for Black dark-squared
bishop! The major advantage of Black's last move is the security of the
kingisde. Now, Black can prevent White's knight from heading to f5 by playing
g6.} ({Black was doing fine also i the following game} 13... Qd7 14. b4 Bf8 15.
Ng3 Rad8 16. Nh2 {Andriasian,Z (2598)-Pashikian,A (2607) Yerevan 2013 Now very
strong would have been} d4 $1 17. Rd1 Re6 {with nice game.}) 14. Ng3 g6 $1 {
[%csl Gf5]} 15. b4 Qd7 {Now Black comfortably completes his development.} 16.
Bd2 Rad8 17. Rad1 Re6 18. Bc1 Rd6 $15 {Black position is better thanks to his
space superiority.} 19. Nd2 Bg7 20. exd5 Rxd5 21. Nde4 Nxe4 22. Nxe4 f5 23. Nc5
Qc8 24. f4 b6 25. Nb3 Qd7 26. fxe5 Rxe5 27. Qf1 Rxe1 28. Qxe1 Qd5 29. Nd2 a5
30. bxa5 Nxa5 31. d4 c5 32. Nf3 Nb3 33. Be3 g5 34. Bf2 b5 35. Nd2 cxd4 36. Nxb3
Qxb3 37. Bxd4 f4 38. Rd2 Bxd4+ 39. Rxd4 Rxd4 40. Qe8+ Kh7 41. cxd4 Qd5 42. Qe7+
Kg6 43. Qc5 Qe4 44. Qxb5 1/2-1/2

