1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. O-O Nf6 5. d3 O-O 6. h3 $5 {We should pay a
special attention to this tricky move order. White's main idea is to avoid the
6.c3 d5 line. Sometimes, White is trying to do the same by playing 6.Bb3.
Kramink's move order, however, is even better since by playing 6.h3, White
keeps open the option of expanding on the queenside by means of a2-a4 followed
by the eventual c2-c3 and b2-b4.} d6 ({It transpires that} 6... d5 {is still
possible. Here we have a very important game played recently} 7. exd5 Nxd5 8.
Re1 Be6 $1 {The key move , otherwise Black is in trouble.} 9. Nbd2 ({In case of
} 9. Nxe5 $2 {Black has a typical tactical solution} Nxe5 10. Rxe5 Bxf2+ {when
the e5-rook is vulnerable.}) 9... f6 10. Nb3 {This plan is flawed and this is
definitely the place where White should look for improvement . I would suggest}
(10. c3 $5 {as a possible idea.}) 10... Bb6 11. d4 Bf7 $1 12. dxe5 Nxe5 13.
Nxe5 fxe5 14. Bxd5 Bxd5 15. Be3 c6 $11 {Black has easily solved his opening
problems in  Van Foreest,J (2578)-Bachmann,A (2642) Teplice 2016}) 7. c3 {This
move is always good when Black had already played d7-d6.} a6 8. Re1 {Another
tricky move order, White keep his bishop on c4 in order to have the
possibility switching to a queenside expanison later.} (8. Bb3) 8... Ba7 {Not
my favourite square , however this is  very popular.} ({If we play the normal} 
8... h6 {What could go for} 9. a4 $1 {Now Black h6-move is somewhat pointless.
Here are two model games} Re8 (9... Ba7 10. Nbd2 Ne7 11. d4 Ng6 12. Bf1 {White
has an improved version of Nepomniashtchi-So Baku 2016. This happened in 
Mamedov,R (2666)-Howell,D (2665) Baku 2016}) 10. Nbd2 Be6 11. Bxe6 Rxe6 12. b4
Ba7 13. Qc2 d5 14. Nb3 {White was clearly better in Karjakin,S (2769)-Navara,D
(2742) Baku 2016}) {Now with Black bishop on a7 White switches to
old-fashioned plan.} 9. Bb3 h6 10. Nbd2 {We have arrived to an extremely
important theoretical position. I am not a big fan a7-bishop (prefer
dark-squared bishop on f8)  , but we have a bunch of high-level games here. At
the end of the day, I think that Black's chances are quite reasonable even in
this line.} Re8 ({Another plan in this position is} 10... Nh5 {one of the key
games in this variation} 11. Nf1 Qf6 {preparing Nf4[%cal Gh5f4]} 12. Be3 Bxe3
13. Nxe3 Nf4 14. Nd5 Nxd5 15. exd5 Ne7 16. d4 Ng6 17. dxe5 dxe5 18. Bc2 Bf5 19.
Bxf5 Qxf5 20. c4 Rad8 $11 {and Black was fine in Admiraal,M (2441)-Adhiban,B 
(2653) Wijk aan Zee 2016}) 11. Nf1 Be6 12. Bc2 {This line is more critical than
} (12. Be3 {Black easliy equalized in th following game} Bxe3 13. Nxe3 d5 14.
Qc2 Qd7 15. Rad1 Rad8 $11 {1/2-1/2 (57) Harikrishna,P (2753)-Mamedyarov,S 
(2747) Huaian 2016}) 12... d5 13. exd5 {Now all three recaptures possible.}
Bxd5 (13... Qxd5 14. Ng3 Rad8 15. b4 $1 Qd6 16. Bd2 $14 {looks better for
White Vovk,A (2632)-Loos,R (2316) Wunsiedel 2016}) (13... Nxd5 14. Ng3 {here
we have a Top GM game played not so long time ago} Qd6 15. Nh4 {White tries to
develop initiative on the kingside} Qd7 $6 16. Qf3 Qe7 17. Nhf5 Qf8 18. Bb3 $40
{with dangerous initiative Giri,A (2778)-So,W (2767) Bilbao 2015}) 14. Ng3 Bc5
{Vishy tries to bring his dark-squared bishop back! However losing two tempi
hardly can be a good idea. I believe Black's best idea here is} (14... Qd7 15.
b4 Rad8 16. a4 b5 $1 {As we already know, this is a typical way to stop
White's queenside expansion.} 17. axb5 axb5 18. Nh4 Bb6 19. Nhf5 Ne7 $1 20.
Nxg7 $2 Kxg7 21. Rxe5 Ng6 $17 {and failed to prove his compensation Nisipeanu,
L (2683)-Mamedyarov,S (2743) Reykjavik 2015}) 15. b4 Bf8 16. a4 g6 (16... b5
17. Ne4 Nd7 {should be better for White after calm developing Nevednichy,V 
(2603)-Mirzoev,A (2536) Izmir 2013} 18. Bd2) 17. Bb2 {threatening 18. b5[%cal
Gb4b5]} b5 18. Ne4 {Another precise move. White takes advantage of the fact
that} Rb8 (18... Nxe4 19. dxe4 Bc4 20. Nd2 Be6 21. Qe2 {clearly worse for
Black.[%csl Ga6,Gb5]}) 19. Bc1 Nd7 20. Bb3 Bxb3 21. Qxb3 Re6 22. axb5 axb5 23.
Be3 {Black pieces are not so well-coordinated.} Nf6 24. Rad1 Nxe4 25. dxe4 Qe8
26. Rd5 $1 $16 {White has emerged with clear edge out of the opening phase.}
Nd8 27. Ra1 Nb7 28. Ra7 c6 29. Rd1 Nd6 30. Nd2 Ra8 31. Rda1 Rxa7 32. Rxa7 Re7
33. Ra6 Rc7 34. Qa2 Kg7 35. Bb6 Rb7 36. Bc5 Be7 37. Ra8 Rb8 38. Ra7 Rd8 39. Bb6
Rc8 40. Bc7 Qd7 41. Bb6 Qe8 42. g3 Bg5 43. Bc7 Bxd2 44. Bxd6 Bxc3 45. Re7 Qg8
46. Qe6 Qf8 47. Kg2 Rd8 48. Bc5 Bd4 49. Qxc6 Kg8 50. Qxb5 Rb8 51. Rxf7 1-0

