1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. O-O Nf6 5. d3 O-O 6. a4 $5 {The latest trend
in this popular line. White gains space on the queenside and triesto delay the
move c2-c3 , as it allows the immediate 6...d5 ( see Anand-So 2016 in this
survey). In general, he would play c2-c3 only after d7-d6.} d6 ({In this
position,} 6... d5 {would be premature. Here is one model game} 7. exd5 Nxd5 8.
Nbd2 $1 Re8 9. Ne4 Bf8 10. c3 h6 11. Bxh6 $1 $18 {1-0 (15) Grischuk,A (2747)
-Makhnyov,D (2345) Almaty 2016[%csl Gf6][%cal Gc4d5]}) 7. c3 {This move is
always an important plan of White's strategy. Besides the obvious idea to
prepare the d3-d4 advance in the future, White creates also a little trap -
now he wants to trap Black's bishop by means of b2-b4.} a6 {I prefer this
modest move. Black creates a room for the bishop without creating weaknesses.}
({Of course, possible is} 7... a5 {One of the recent games in this line
continued} 8. Na3 d5 9. exd5 Nxd5 10. Nb5 Nb6 11. Bg5 Be7 12. Bxe7 Qxe7 13. Bb3
Bg4 14. Qe2 Rad8 $13 {Black achieved comfortable game in David,A (2572)
-Sokolov,I (2635) Saint Quentin 2016}) 8. h3 {As we already know, White's idea
is to start gradually preparing the d3-d4 advance. Most probably, his next
moves will be Re1, Nbd2-f1-g3 followed by d3-d4. Before going Re1, however, it
is important to take the g4-square from the knight.} ({Another important line
here is} 8. Nbd2 Ba7 9. h3 Ne7 {This is a very thematic idea for this type of
positions. The reader shoud know that the c6-knight is Black's worst piece in
the position since the c7-pawn couldn't participate in the fight for the
centre. That is why Black is going for the manouevre Nc6-e7-g6. Later on,
Black has to decent plans:  1) fight for the centre by means of c7-c6 followed
by d6-d5  2) develop a kingside initiative by playing Nh5 and Qf6.} 10. Re1 Ng6
{And here we have a bunch of high-level games:} 11. d4 {This move is the most
ambitious one.} (11. Bb3 {has occured only once} Re8 ({I would suggest another
idea as a possible improvement} 11... Nh5 $5 {As we have already mentioned,
this is a typical idea for the position. Black intends to continue 12...Nhf4
followed by Qf6, thus creating interesting play on the kingside.[%cal Gh5f4]})
12. d4 h6 13. Bc2 c6 14. Nf1 d5 15. Nxe5 Nxe5 16. dxe5 Nxe4 17. Bxe4 dxe4 18.
Qxd8 Rxd8 {Anand,V (2770)-Aronian,L (2792) Saint Louis 2016  After precise} 19.
Be3 $1 $146 Bb8 20. Bd4 $14 {White looks better.}) (11. Nf1 c6 12. Bb3 d5 $1 {
Just in time.} 13. exd5 Nxd5 14. d4 ({The e5-pawn is untouchable since after} 
14. Nxe5 $2 {Black has} Nxe5 15. Rxe5 Bxf2+ $1 {when White's kingside is
seriously weakened.}) 14... exd4 15. Nxd4 Be6 $1 {This is how Black solves the
problem of developing his light-squared bishop.} 16. Bc2 {Capturing
light-squared bishop allows Black to develop nice initiative on the kingisde} (
16. Nxe6 fxe6 17. Be3 Bxe3 18. Nxe3 Qh4 $1) 16... Qf6 $11 {Black was perfectly
fine in Caruana,F (2795)-So,W (2773) Saint Louis 2016}) 11... h6 12. Bf1 Re8
13. a5 Bd7 14. b4 {Kramnik,V (2808)-Radjabov,T (2722) Baku 2016\  Vladimir won
a very nice game , however this was a great moment for Black to strike with
the thematic} d5 $1 {and Black is doing great after both} 15. dxe5 {and} (15.
exd5 e4 16. Nh2 Nxd5) 15... Nxe4 16. Nxe4 dxe4 17. Rxe4 Bc6 $1 18. Re1 Qxd1 19.
Rxd1 Bxf3 20. gxf3 Nxe5 $11) 8... Ba7 9. Re1 (9. Nbd2 {see 8. Nbd2}) 9... Ne7 {
Again the same thematic idea.} 10. d4 Ng6 11. Bd3 (11. Nbd2 {see 8. Nbd2})
11... c6 {This is more precise than} (11... Re8 12. Qc2 Bd7 13. Be3 d5 14. Nbd2
exd4 15. cxd4 dxe4 16. Nxe4 Bc6 17. Bg5 $1 {and White was better in Kramnik,V 
(2801)-Aronian,L (2784) Stavanger 2016}) 12. Be3 Nh5 {Another thematic idea,
Black knight is heading to f4.} 13. Nbd2 Nhf4 14. Bf1 exd4 $1 {Wesley shows a
very deep understanding of this variation. There cannot be a better moment to
change the pawnstructure in the center.} 15. Bxd4 (15. cxd4 d5 16. e5 a5 {We
have reached a very important pawn structure for the variation. The passivity
of White's e3-bishop, explains the move 15.Bxd4. Black's idea consists in
eliminating White's space advantage by playing f7-f6. It is important to point
out that after f7-f6 break, all black pieces come into play. Later on, Black
could combine his pressure against the weak d4-pawn with threats on the f-file.
}) 15... Bxd4 16. cxd4 d5 $1 {Of course! Black goes for the favourbale
structure we are already familiar with.} 17. e5 f6 18. Ra3 fxe5 19. dxe5 $6 {
White would maintain equality after accurate} (19. Nxe5 $1 Nxe5 20. Rxe5 Ng6
21. Re1 Bf5 $11) 19... a5 $1 {[%csl Gb4]} 20. Qc1 Qe7 21. Rb3 Bf5 {Another
important positional move - before playing Ne6, Black wants to develop his
bishop.} 22. Nd4 Ne6 $1 23. Nxf5 Rxf5 $17 {Black emerged from the opening
phase with clearly better game and later on proceeded to win one of the most
decisive games of Chess Olympiad.} 24. Bd3 Rf4 25. Bxg6 hxg6 26. Qd1 Raf8 27.
Rf3 Qb4 28. Rxf4 Rxf4 29. Nf3 Qxa4 30. Qd3 Rf5 31. Qb1 Qf4 32. Qc2 Kh7 33. Re3
Qc4 34. Qd1 Rf4 35. Rc3 Qb4 36. Qc1 a4 37. h4 Kg8 38. Qb1 Qe4 39. Qd1 Nd4 40.
Re3 Nxf3+ 41. gxf3 Qf5 42. e6 Rxh4 43. Re4 Rxe4 44. fxe4 Qxe4 45. Qd2 Qxe6 46.
Qa5 Qg4+ 47. Kf1 b5 48. Qc7 g5 49. Qb8+ Kh7 50. Qd6 b4 0-1

