1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. O-O Nf6 5. d3 d6 6. c3 a6 7. a4 {The latest
trend as we already know.} O-O {Black has two major alternatives 8...h6 and 8..
.Ba7 but I prefer the text.} 8. Bg5 {A very challenging move with a lot of
developments recently. In positions where Black has already castled, the pin
along the h4-d8 diagonal could be really annoying since the plans connected
with ...h7-h6 and g7-g5 could be risky. Moreover, Black couldn't go for the
standart idea Nc6-e7-g6 because his kingside pawn structure will be ruined. By
the way, this is the reason why sometimes Black doesn't makes a castle on move
8.} h6 {Despite the abovementioned considerations, I am convinced that Black
should get rid of the pin. My analysis show that the arising positions are not
as dangerous as they seem to be.} 9. Bh4 g5 10. Bg3 ({I am pretty sure that} 
10. Nxg5 {is not too dangerous for Black. Here is one high-level game} hxg5 11.
Bxg5 Kg7 12. Qf3 Rh8 13. Nd2 Kg6 $1 14. h4 $2 (14. Be3 {could have been played.
In this case, Black has at least draw} Kg7 15. Bg5 Kg6 {etc.}) 14... Bg4 $1 15.
Bxf6 Qd7 $1 {The point behind Black's 14th move.} 16. Qg3 Kxf6 17. d4 exd4 18.
e5+ Ke7 19. Ne4 Rag8 $19 {and Black has a winning advantage Caruana,F (2804)
-Nakamura,H (2787) Paris 2016}) 10... Ba7 {An obivous prophylaxis against
possible d3-d4.} 11. Nbd2 {White has been also trying another route for his
knight} (11. Na3 {Here I believe the critical line} Bg4 12. Nc2 {Another game
here went} (12. Re1 Nh5 13. h3 $1 Bxf3 14. Qxf3 Nxg3 15. Qxg3 Qf6 16. Re2 Ne7
17. Nc2 Kg7 18. Rd1 Qf4 19. Qxf4 exf4 {and Black shouldn't have too many
problems in this endgame Neiksans,A (2614)-Lalith,B (2565) Warsaw 2016}) 12...
d5 $5 13. exd5 Nxd5 14. d4 exd4 15. cxd4 Bh5 $13 {with very complex middlegame
Dragun,K (2594)-Gajewski,G (2633) Poznan 2016}) 11... Kg7 12. Re1 Nh7 {With
this move, Black starts preparing a pawn expansion on the kingside. For
example, if he is allowed, he could follow with h6-h5.} ({Peter improves over} 
12... Be6 $6 {which didn't work well for Black in the following game} 13. b4 g4
14. Nh4 Ne7 15. Bxe6 fxe6 16. Nc4 $16 {0-1 (42) Topalov,V (2761)-So,W (2770)
Leuven 2016}) 13. d4 {Classical approach to the position - in response to
Black's attacking ideas on the kingside, White strikes in the centre.} g4 {
Accepting the challenge.} (13... h5 $5 {Can be an interesting alternative}) 14.
Nh4 exd4 15. cxd4 Bxd4 16. Nf1 Bf6 $2 {Peter commits a serious error under
pressure. I believe the position would be very unclear after the precise} (
16... Nf6 $1 17. Ne3 Bxe3 18. Rxe3 Nh5 $1) 17. Nf5+ Bxf5 18. exf5 h5 19. Bf4
Bg5 (19... Ne5 {was necessary , still after} 20. Bd5 $1 c6 21. Bb3 {White
initiative looks threatening.}) 20. Ng3 Kh6 21. Bc1 $3 {This is a remarkable
idea, which leads to White clear advantage. It seems} (21. Nxh5 Kxh5 22. Ra3 $1
$40 {was pretty strong as well.[%cal Ga3h3]}) 21... Bxc1 22. Rxc1 Ne5 23. Ba2
Nf6 24. Qd2+ Kh7 25. Qg5 Rg8 26. Qh4 $40 {White attack was too poweful and
even such a great defender as Peter Leko was unable to defend this position.}
Nfd7 27. Qxh5+ Kg7 28. f6+ Qxf6 29. Rxc7 Kf8 30. Rxb7 Qg6 31. Qf5 Qxf5 32. Nxf5
Rg6 33. b4 Rf6 34. Ne3 Rc8 35. Bb1 Rf4 36. Bf5 Rb8 37. Ra7 Nf6 38. Rxa6 Rbxb4
39. Rxd6 Ne8 40. Rd5 f6 41. Bc2 Rb2 42. Ra1 Nc4 43. Rb5 Rxb5 44. axb5 Nxe3 45.
fxe3 Rc4 46. Bg6 Nd6 47. Rb1 g3 48. hxg3 Rc7 49. Bd3 Nc8 50. Kf2 Nb6 51. Ra1
Rd7 52. Ra6 Rd6 53. Be4 Ke7 54. Kf3 1-0

