1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. O-O d6 5. c3 Nf6 6. d3 h6 {Michael prevents
White'ń idea of Bg5, however I have always thought it's not so dangerous as
Black can push White's dark-squared bishop to g3.} 7. Re1 O-O 8. h3 {Kramnik's
move order.} a5 $5 {This is a bit refreshing in this position, however in
general quite common idea. Black not only creates a a room for his
dark-squared bishop but also to stop b2-b4 move and gain some space on the
queenside. An obvious drawback of Black'ń last move is the weakness of the
b5-square.[%csl Gb5]} 9. Bb3 {White's most natural reaction. Definitely, White
has tried other option in this rich position.} (9. a4 {occured in a very
recent game, where Black got a comfortable game after} Be6 10. Na3 Bxa3 $1 {
Thematic idea in this line.} 11. Bxe6 Bxb2 12. Bxf7+ Rxf7 13. Bxb2 Qd7 14. c4
Raf8 15. Nh4 Kh7 $13 {Hou,Y (2649)-Caruana,F (2813) Douglas 2016}) (9. Nbd2 Be6
10. Bb5 Qb8 $5 {Remember this queen's manoeuvre  Black's queen is heading for
the a7-square where it will help to generate pressure against f2.[%cal Gb8a7]}
11. Nf1 Qa7 12. Re2 {this all happened in the game Garcia Moreno,C (2285)
-Valles Moreno,I (2447) Linares 2016 Black should have played} a4 $1 {with a
comfortable position.}) 9... Re8 10. Nbd2 Be6 {It goes without saying, that
this is one of Black's main ideas in this variation. We should always try to
neutralize White's light-squared bishop.} 11. Ba4 {This seems like the most
challenging for White. In case of} (11. Bc2 {Black is ready for} d5 12. Qe2 {
occured in Wolter,K (2241)-Hogenacker,J (2276) Germany 2005. Now Black should
have played} a4 $1 $146 13. exd5 Qxd5 14. Ne4 Be7 {with comfortable position.})
11... Qb8 $1 {Michael comes up with an elegant improvement over} (11... Ba7 12.
Nf1 Rb8 13. Bb5 Bd7 14. Ng3 Ne7 15. Bxd7 Qxd7 16. d4 Ng6 17. Be3 exd4 18. Bxd4
Bxd4 19. cxd4 $14 {and Black failed to fully solve his opening problems
Harikrishna,P (2752)-Karjakin,S (2769) Baku 2016}) 12. d4 (12. Bb5 {should be
met with} Qa7 13. Qe2 a4 {with good game for Black.}) 12... exd4 13. cxd4 b5 $1
{The point behind Black 11...Qb8 - novelty} 14. dxc5 bxa4 15. cxd6 cxd6 {My
impression that Black's activity fully compensates his sagnificantly damaged
pawn strucutre.} 16. Nb1 ({Better would have been} 16. Qxa4 Qb6 $1 {Black has
a full compensation for the pawn. For instance} 17. Nc4 Bxc4 18. Qxc4 Rxe4 $1
19. Rxe4 d5 $11) 16... d5 $1 17. exd5 Bxd5 {Black has equalized and proceeded
to win later on.} 18. Rxe8+ Qxe8 19. Be3 Rc8 20. Nc3 Bxf3 21. Qxf3 a3 22. Qe2
Qe5 23. Rd1 Ne7 24. Qd2 Nf5 25. Bf4 Qc5 26. Rc1 axb2 27. Qxb2 Qd4 28. Qd2 Ne4
29. Nxe4 Rxc1+ 30. Qxc1 Qxe4 31. Bg3 a4 32. Kh2 Kh7 33. a3 Nd4 34. Qf4 Qxf4 35.
Bxf4 Kg6 36. g4 Kf6 37. Bd6 h5 38. f4 Ke6 39. Bf8 hxg4 40. hxg4 g6 41. Kg3 Kd5
42. g5 Kc4 43. Kg4 Kb3 44. f5 gxf5+ 45. Kg3 f4+ 46. Kg4 f3 47. Kg3 Kc4 48. Kf2
Kd3 49. Bc5 Ne6 50. Be3 Ke4 51. Bc1 Nf4 52. Bd2 Nh3+ 53. Kg3 f2 0-1

