variation.} 8. exf6 {If White takes the pawn (8.Qxd3 or 8.Bxd3) then Black is
just fine after 8...Ng4 attacking f2 and e5 pawns.} dxe2 9. Qxe2+ Kf8 {My
analysis shows that Black is doing very well in this unbalanced position.} *

